This assignment is stored on the following Github repository.

This project uses data from Open Data DC on crime incidents in DC from 2010 to 2022, as well as demographic data from the Census’s 5-year surveys, to study how DC’s crime rates and types of crime have changed over the course of the COVID-19 pandemic and over the ten years leading up to the pandemic. In this analysis, we first explore DC’s crime counts and rates through data visualization, then use lasso regression to predict the number of crimes in DC in a given year.

Our data visualizations and predictive modeling can provide policymakers a better understanding of the types, frequency, and patterns of crimes reported in DC. More importantly, it provides an in-depth look at what factors contribute to crime in DC both pre and post pandemic, informing policymakers on potential ways to address crimes in DC.

Creating Datasets on Crime Incidents

The geojson files come from Open Data DC, the District of Columbia’s open source database. From this database, we gathered DC crime data from 2010 to 2022 which includes crimes reported in different areas of DC with information such as report date, type of offense, location of crime incident, and time of event. From this data, we created two datasets: crime_data_total, which includes DC crime incidents reported from 2019 to 2022, and crime_data_2010s, which includes DC crime incidents reported from 2010 to 2019.

Converting Data and Creating Counts of the Number of Crimes

In order to analyze this data, we converted our datasets into four different datasets:

crime_data_total_2: We separated and converted the crime incident report date into a ‘Date’ classification using our “crime_data_total” dataset.

crime_data_2010s_2: We separated and converted the crime incident report date into a ‘Date’ classification using our “crime_data_2010s” dataset.

crime_count: We filtered, grouped, and summarized our “crime_data_total_2” dataset to create a dataset with the number of crimes reported in January, February, and March in the years 2019 to 2022.

crime_graph_data: We grouped and summarized our “crime_data_total_2” to create a dataset counting the number of crimes reported by date from 2019 to 2022.

crime_data_total_2 <- crime_data_total %>%
  separate(
    col = report_dat,
    into = c("date", "time"),
    sep = " ",
    remove = FALSE
  ) %>%
  mutate(year = year(date),
         month = month(date),
         day = day(date),
         ymd = paste(year, month, day, sep = "-"),
         date2 = as.Date(ymd)) 

crime_count <- crime_data_total_2 %>%
  filter(month < 4,
         !is.na(ward))%>%
  group_by(ward, year) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() 

crime_graph_data <- crime_data_total_2 %>%
  group_by(date2) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() 

crime_data_2010s_2 <- crime_data_2010s %>%
  separate(
    col = report_dat,
    into = c("date", "time"),
    sep = " ",
    remove = FALSE
  ) %>%
  mutate(year = year(date),
         month = month(date)) 

crime_count_2010s <- crime_data_2010s_2 %>%
  filter(!is.na(ward))%>%
  group_by(ward, year) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  st_drop_geometry()

Exploratory Analysis of Crime in DC Between 2019 and 2022

The bar chart below visualizes number of crimes reported in each ward by type of offense in Washington, DC from 2019 to 2022. We also provide a map of DC’s 8 wards below for reference.

DC.gov: Wards of the District of Columbia

Based on the visualization below, arson, homicide, and sex abuse are the least commonly reported crimes, while theft is the most common. The ward with the highest overall crime counts is Ward 2, where Georgetown University is located.

#Type of Crime Committed by Crime Count
crime_data_total_2 %>%
  filter(!is.na(ward)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(offense, fill = ward)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(
    title = "Number of Crimes by Type of Offense in Washington, DC (2019 - 2022)",
    subtitle = "By Ward",
    x = "Type of Criminal Offense",
    y = "Crime Count",
    fill = "Ward",
    caption = "Open Data DC. Crime Incidents in years 2019 to 2022."
  ) + 
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust=1))

The bar chart below visualizes number of crimes reported in all of DC from 2019 to 2022 based on the shift time (Day, Evening, Midnight) the crime was reported. Based on the visualization, the evening shift has the most reported crimes and the midnight shift has the least.

The 4 bar charts below reflect the number of crimes in Washington, DC by ward for the months January to March in the years 2019, 2020, 2021, and 2022. Overall, crimes vastly decreased during the pandemic years (2021-2022) compared to pre-pandemic ones (2019-2020).

The scatter plots below visualize crime counts in all of DC during the Holiday season (November to January) from 2019 to 2022. In both scatter plots, Thanksgiving, Christmas Eve, and Christmas Day have low crime counts than other days. However, the days surrounding these holidays differ in crime count between 2020-2021 and 2021-2022 with some crime significantly increasing after one of the holidays.

Exploratory Analysis of Crime in DC Between 2010 and 2019

The animated bar graph explores the number of crimes reported by ward from the years 2010 to 2019. Over the past decade, crime rates varied year by year. In 2016, mostly all of DC’s wards significantly increased in crimes reported compared to the other years. Additionally, Ward 2 was consistently the highest in crimes reported from 2010 to 2019.

#Animated plot for change in crime over time
crime_over_time <- crime_count_2010s %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = ward, y = count, fill = ward)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs (
    title = "Number of Crimes in Washington, DC in {frame_time}",
    subtitle = "By Ward",
    x = "Ward",
    y = "Number of Crimes",
    caption = "Open Data DC. Crime Incidents in years 2010 to 2019.",
  ) + 
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Ward") +
  transition_time(as.integer(year)) +
  ease_aes('linear')

#animate graph
animate(crime_over_time, nframes = 10, duration = 10, fps = 1, width = 400, height = 400, renderer = gifski_renderer())

pop_map

The maps illustrated below reflect the crime rate by tract in the years 2010 to 2019. According to the maps, the distribution of crime rates have remained relatively consistent through the decade. Most crime is concentrated in highly populated tracts in downtown DC.

crimerate_map

The map below visualizes crimes reported in DC in 2021 (light pink) and the location of police stations (blue). We can see that there are more police stations in high-crime reported areas. We also see that many crimes are concentrated on busy roads, namely Connecticut Ave, Wisconsin Ave, and Georgia Ave

crime_police21

Based the data visualizations above, crime decreased overall during the pandemic, which is most likely due to the pandemic shutdowns that took place in 2020 and the slow reopening/use of of shops, restaurants, workplaces, and transit in 2021 and 2022.
